Here is the translation of the conversation into simple English.

**Note:** The original text contains "Singlish" (Singaporean English) and Chinese dialects (like Hokkien and Cantonese). The translation below captures the meaning and tone while removing the local slang for clarity.

***

**Alice:**
Haha.
Yeah, me too.
I really like playing, but I never gamble.
:)

**Bob:**
Oh... I never gamble on Big Two either.
Except for that one time a few weeks ago.

**Alice:**
Oh, did you lose money a few weeks ago?

**Bob:**
I went to a friend’s house.
He wanted to play Big Two.
I said, "Okay, let’s play."
He said, "One cent per card..." (because he is very good at the game).
I thought, "Okay, fine." Besides, I would only lose at most $10.

**Alice:**
Oh, you lost.
:)
Haha. It’s okay, you just had bad luck.
It’s actually fine. But if you gamble, you won’t be able to enjoy the game fully.

**Bob:**
But it’s not good to be so stubborn about not gambling.
Yeah, if you have to gamble, it’s very stressful.
By the way, do you have the software/program for the game?

**Alice:**
What program?
I don’t have it.
You need to download it or something.
:)

**Bob:**
Well, if you want to play online, you need a program to play.
My current chat client doesn’t support file transfers yet. Maybe I can send it to you via FTP or HTTP... wait a moment.

**Alice:**
Okay.
:)
No problem.
Haha. [end of text]


